<br>
In the case of the skeletal jester in Kurn's, the proper PNP solution is as follows: when the new person showed up, he should have asked if the jester was camped, if it was he should have let the person already there take next jester spawn, then he should have gotten the one after that, and they should have taken turns like reasonable adults.<br>
<br>
That way one person can't hog a spawn, and another person can't simply evict you from where you're hunting. It's called &quot;compromise&quot; and it's the polite way to go. Is this horribly tedious? Yes. I've camped that spawn, and you can go several hours without seeing a jester, let alone getting a club. It's rude to jump someone's camp AND it's rude not to share a camp.<br>
<br>
Of course, this game has many rude people and that ideal is rarely met. Quite often, someone just comes and takes the camp without talking first, which results in defensive behavior and a quarrel.<br>
<br>
I think Xarshul's story is an obvious case of rudeness on BOTH sides. Was it rude for people in need of bonechips to interrupt your power-leveling? Yes. Was it rude for you to not allow them to share? Yes. Here's a thought, try being nice to each other and take turns. Even if that means you have to be the grown-up and initiate the niceness and sharing.<br>
<br>
I guess I'm a sucker, but if I was a 42nd level necro PLing a young chanter, and a couple people came up and said they needed some bone chips, I would have reacted like this. &quot;/say OK, we'll gladly share with you. Feel free to take the next skeleton and we'll alternate.&quot; or perhaps &quot;/say I have a bunch of bone chips, how about I give you some, so that my friend and I can continue hunting the skeletons.&quot;<br>
<br>
Or you can just wipe them out with your 40-something pet and make sure nobody wins...but that seems petty and childish to me (and a clear violation of the PNP requirement of sharing spawns). If you had actually tried to share with the newcomers and they KSed you, then I'd have sympathy for you. But you didn't even give them a chance to share. They were rude for jumping your camp, and you were rude for not sharing. Sounds like neither group played nice. <p>Grimwyrd Storm<BR>
(Lux Aeternam)<BR>
29th Human Druid of Karana<BR></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugrimwyrd.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimwyrd</A> at: 1/1/02 4:40:04 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umheddik.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mheddik</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 72<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/1/02 4:51:29 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   You have to share, that is the rule</span><hr size=1> You may not LIKE it, but that's the way it is.<br>
<br>
The only time I actually ever had anyone demand to share a camp was on another server. I had cleared the king room in Permafrost, had all the timing down, and a group came in and wanted their turn. So, to be fair, I said we would share the camp, but that they had to wait til everything respawned, then they could have their turn clearing the whole thing, then I would do the same, and so on. (Yes, I still got experience from at least many of those monsters, though not the weakest.)<br>
<br>
Well, they *couldn't* clear that room themselves. They wanted to reap the benefits of my having done so first. Note that they didn't ask. I had been ready to leave and would have gladly turned the camp over to them and stayed a round to make sure they had it under control if they had even pretended to be polite. But since they DEMANDED rather than make any attempt at politeness, well, I didn't see any reason to be considerate myself, so I decided NOT to leave. Consideration begets consideration. In any case, it was a greay area of the PvP, so I had called a GM myself and he agreed with me, that a complete fresh clearing of the area for each group was reasonable. Since they couldn't handle what they wanted without me having made it easy for them first, they left. After they'd been gone from Permafrost for 30 minutes, THEN I left.<br>
<br>
If someone invokes the PnP on me at a camp, I always share. I may tell them that the experience is now going to suck for both of us, no point in lying if that is the case, but I always share or, at worst, I go elsewhere. If it's a camp that takes significant work to break and they at least ask politely, I let them reap the rewards of my breaking and timing things. If they demand, then they can do it from scratch which is really the more challenging way for them to do it (which isn't necessarily bad but kinda sucks for them if they *can't* do that themselves).<br>
<br>
In any case, I tend to ramble. If I have a point, I guess it's nothing more than 'being polite is always good' and that applies to whether you are the person with the camp or the person who wants the camp.<br>
<br>
Coriolis of Erudin, Firiona Vie, Illusionist<br>
